,"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1065–":"circa 1065–Overleden","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1085–1108":"1085–1108","1100–Male":"1100–Overleden","1065–Female":"1065–Overleden","Abt 1065":"circa 1065","110":"1100","Abt 1085":"circa 1085","1100":"1100","1065":"1065","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1060":"1060","1108":"1108","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Richmond, Yorkshire, England":"Richmond, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridgeshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1065–":"about 1065–Deceased","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1085–1108":"1085–1108","1100–Male":"1100–Deceased","1065–Female":"1065–Deceased","Abt 1065":"about 1065","110":"1100","Abt 1085":"about 1085","1100":"1100","1065":"1065","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1060":"1060","1108":"1108","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Richmond, Yorkshire, England":"Richmond, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chamberlain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: status name from Old French <i>chambrelain</i>, Norman French <i>cambrelanc</i>, <i>cambrelen(c)</i> ‘chamberlain’ (of ancient Germanic origin, from <i>kamer</i> ‘chamber, room’, Latin <i>camera</i> (see   Chambers  ) + the diminutive suffix <i>-(l)ing</i>). This was originally the name of an official in charge of the private chambers of his master, but is so widespread in late medieval England that it must sometimes have been used of people of more ordinary status, perhaps as a nickname for an officious or self-important person or for someone who played the role of chamberlain in a folk play, tableau, or ceremony. Compare   Chancellor   for a possible similar usage."],"variants":[{"name":"Chamberlin","meanings":["English: variant of   Chamberlain  .","French: occupational name for an official in charge of the private chambers of his master, from Old French <i>chamberlenc</i> ‘chamberlain’. See also   Chamberlain   and compare above."]},{"name":"Chambers","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>chaumbre</i> ‘room (in a house); reception room in a palace or official building’ (Old French <i>chambre</i>). It is identical in implied function with the   Chamberlain  , which denoted an official: to pay <i>in cameram</i> was to pay into the exchequer, of which the <i>camerarius</i> or chamberer was in charge. The surname also applied to clerks employed there. As the office of <i>Chamberlain</i> rose in the social scale, this term remained reserved for more humble servants of the bedchamber or private quarters.","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Les Chambres, Manche (France)."]}]},{"name":"Odo","type":"FIRST","meanings":["the Celtic name Aodh has been Anglicised into Hugh, and Latinised variously Hugo, Ædus, Ædanus, Aidus, and Odo."],"variants":[]},{"name":"the","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a variant spelling of   Ty   or a transferred use of the surname, a local name for someone who lived by a common pasture, Middle English <i>tye</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Odo the Chamberlain was born about 1065, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. She married Odo the Chamberlain about 1085, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in Richmond, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1065–":"umbes 1065–Surnud","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1085–1108":"1085–1108","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1065–Female":"1065–Surnud","Abt 1065":"umbes 1065","110":"1100","Abt 1085":"umbes 1085","1100":"1100","1065":"1065","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1060":"1060","1108":"1108","Gloucester